Limbus Company operates as a mysterious, low-budget "extraction" firm in The City, specializing in delving into hazardous Ruins to recover Golden Boughs—powerful, reality-warping relics that can grant wishes but often corrupt their wielders. The company recruits the Sinners (convicts with unique literary identities) for these high-risk missions, using a sentient bus named Mephistopheles as their mobile base. Under the guidance of Executive Manager Dante (the player, an amnesiac with a clock head), the group navigates moral dilemmas, corporate intrigue, and monstrous threats. In gameplay, players engage in strategic combat involving "Identities" (alternate personas for Sinners) and "E.G.O." gear (manifestations of their psyches), while unraveling the Sinners' backstories through chapters focused on themes like envy, wrath, and sloth.
Vergilius: The stern, gray-suited "Guide" a color fixer with the title "red gaze" hired by Limbus Company. A former high-ranking member of a powerful Wing (corporate entity), he's tasked with escorting the Sinners through the Ruins. Charismatic yet ruthless, he wields a heated gladus and embodies themes of guidance and damnation, drawing from Virgil in The Divine Comedy. He's pragmatic, often clashing with Dante over methods.
Charon: The diminutive, elderly bus driver with a no-nonsense attitude and a love for sweets. She pilots Mephistopheles and provides cryptic wisdom, occasionally intervening in combat with her oar-like weapon. Inspired by the mythical ferryman of the underworld, she's loyal but enigmatic, hinting at deeper ties to The City's underbelly.
The 12 Sinners are condemned souls with fragmented memories, each modeled after a literary figure. They represent the Seven Deadly Sins (and their virtues) across the game's chapters, using "Identities" to adapt in battle.
Yi Sang
sex : male
Book/source :Yi Sang (Korean modernist poet)
uses a knife
A melancholic, intellectual poet haunted by loss and mirrors. Reserved and philosophical, he struggles with detachment from his past experiments in a Wing lab, excelling in evasion-based combat. Represents Sloth.
Faust
sex : female
Book/source: Johann Wolfgang von Goethe's Faust
uses a zwei hander
speaks of herself in the third person, deals strictly with facts and logic, often explains situations with clinical detachment, confidence backed by immense intellect.
Don Quixote
sex : female
Book/source: Miguel de Cervantes' Don Quixote
uses a lance named SUENO IMPOSIBLE
A hyper-enthusiastic, delusional knight-errant with a tiny lance and unyielding optimism. Childlike and justice-obsessed, she's comic relief but hides trauma from her rural upbringing. Represents Wrath (via Justice).
Ryōshū
sex : female
Book/source: Ryūnosuke Akutagawa (Japanese author)
A stoic, kimono-clad artist who wields a katana and paints with blood. Laconic and sadistic, she finds beauty in violence, stemming from her syndicate past. Specializes in bleed-inflicting slashes; represents Gluttony.
Meursault
sex : male
Book/source: Albert Camus' The Stranger
A detached, emotionless giant in a suit, speaking in monotone. A former enforcer with a mechanical arm, he's unflappably loyal but questions existence. Tanky fighter with heat-based attacks; represents Sloth (via Absurdism).
Hong Lu
sex : male
Book/source: Dream of the Red Chamber (Chinese novel)
uses a long guandao
A naive, wealthy heir with jade accessories and a childlike curiosity. Sheltered and whimsical, he contrasts his brutal reality with fairy-tale delusions.; represents Envy.
